This is a simple tension locking mechanism. With the new MK6's ability for rapid reversal, the simple tension screw would gradually jiggle lose. And while I know there are several different designs for the new extruders that prevent this, I did not want to take a bunch of time to print and replace the old acrylic frame. Solution? Design a lock system to prevent the screw from coming lose!
10 minutes to design, 30 minutes to print the pieces, and my quick fix is ready and working!

Print a tension lock.
Print a Locking bar. (Version 2 is much better, but both are listed).
Glue the circular part to the screw. Tension it how you would like.
Drop the locking bar in place, as close to the correct tension as you would like. NOTE:
Rubber band -> Self Tension?

comments.text: Note that I figured a rubber band combined with this might make it somewhat of a self tension kind of thing, but I'm still currently testing it out.

title: Blower fan adapter for active cooling duct for CTC/Flashforge - UPDATED

description.text:
I really liked the original active cooling duct, keeping the air flow directly aimed towards whatever is currently being printed instead of just general air flow. This meant that smaller details have a better chance of printing well. The issue arises that typical axial fans are designed for just air flow, not for providing enough air pressure to force it around bends and curves like what has been implemented with the cooling duct.

Blowers on the other hand can provide slightly better pressure so I took it upon myself to design an adapter that fitted the original duct which utilised a blower fan that is small enough to fit within the confines of the machine.

UPDATE:-

Just uploaded an updated version, much shorter, less noisier!

Print however you feel necessary. I used 2 outlines, 20% infill, 0.4mm nozzle and clear PLA.
I would recommend however using a small support under the screw hole on the arm that sticks out to the side as the curve overhangs a little too much to print reliably.

G92 E0 ; Reset extruder position

{IF_EXT0}M109 T0 S{TEMP0}

This model is the tetrahedron defined by equations y=−6, z=0, z=x+4, and 2x+y+z=4. The equations are printed on the model.

This model was designed and printed by my WLU summer research student Ryan McDonnell ('17). See http://mathvis.academic.wlu.edu/2015/07/14/tetrahedra/ for more information.

You may have to scale by a factor of 10 if you're using MakerWare, since it tends to import files in mm, not cm. Object is sized to be 12cm in the longest dimension, but smaller prints should work just fine.

This object was made on a MakerBot2X. We used the following settings:
2 shells
0.20mm layer height
10% infill (hexagonal pattern)
No supports
raft off

We printed the object with the z=0 face as the base. Thus, we needed to add some ABS juice to the build bed to be sure the object stuck and didn't curl up at the corners.

title: intensewalkera Hague MMC mini motion cam / steadycam - GoPro / Contour / small Generic cam adapter V3 Final

description.text:
Hague MMC mini motion cam / steadycam - GoPro / Contour / small Generic cam adapter V3 Final Anyone with a Hague steadycam will know how hard it is to get these smaller cameras balanced. this lifts the COG and allows more weight to be added to the camera and therefore makes it easier to balance.
for my GoPro in the case, i added 4 of the large weights to the topside and balanced it with two large weights on the bottom.
To assemble
  • You need a standard 1/4 inch whitworth nut, glued in the btm half.
  • Glue an M5 boltx10mm-15mm in the middle section (bolt head on the underside)
    3.Glue and install the middle piece.
  • select the required top camera interface and glue in place using the tabs as guides.
  • install required weights and hold in place with an M5 nut
  • screw on top of hague steadycam and balance as needed
    • ive supplied a GoPro top, Contour Roam top and a generic top.
    the generic top is supplied with two holes to allow for anyone that needs an offset, it also comes with a finger wheel, that can be used on a 1/4 inch whitworth bolt( glued in place) to be used to attach to a standard camera mount. ive only made the Gopro version, but ive used the Contour layout on other camera mounts and i know it works. any feedback is appreciated as to if any issues arise with them, like i say ive only made an pre V3 version, which i modified for the better to make this one.

This is my entry for the MakeItFloat contest. This was my first big project so there might be some printing mistakes or other things that could be done better.
I based my boat on the Maersk container ships and I made working containers in a stack of 2x3 (they would be too big on their own) that you can open and put coins and stuff in. The deck is magnetically attached to the hull and is easily removable. There is room in the hull for storage or whatever else you want to put because I suppose you could make it Rc with some mods or turn it into a "pop pop" boat like those other entries. I don't know, the point is I worked hard on this. You could even probably print a mini version of the entire boat so you don't have to assemble anything. The full boat is attached if you want to try to make it in one shot. Right now it is just a pretty cool design that I made that is a platform for anyone who wants to turn it into something really cool.
It can hold a good amount of weight and if you're wondering why I'm using bolts, it's because I didn't have any coins.
Size:
108.6W x 380.92L x 145.01H mm

If you want to use readjust anything on here, just search for MakeItFloat container ship on Tinkercad. Or 2x3 shipping crates. If you don't use Tinkercad, I'm sorry but it's the only design program i know how to use and it's pretty easy if you don't know how.
Here:
https://www.tinkercad.com/search/?q=makeitfloat+container+ship
https://www.tinkercad.com/search/?q=2x3+shipping+crates

I worked really hard on this. If you have any questions just ask. Ill be here waiting for people to hopefully like this project.
Thanks for looking!

I split the boat up into pieces which is what the downloads are.
There is:
front hull
back hull
front deck
back deck
bridge
front pole
2x3 shipping crates (you can make as many as you would like)

I used hot glue to attach all the pieces but to attach the deck to the hull I drilled 1/8 inch holes into the hull and glued in magnets, then did the same to the deck.(be careful with this)
Here are my settings from when I printed everything (which was on an Ultimaker 2:
layer height: .2
For everything but the hull I used 1.2 shell thickness and bottom/top thickness.
For the hull I used 1.6 to make it stronger.
(you should probably adjust those settings to make it more water tight, it was my first time making 3d stuff so i didn't really know and the hull leaked a lot)
Lastly, I coated the hull in clear aquarium sealant to make it water resistant but you can use any sort of sealant to do this. (probably wasn't smart to use this stuff but it was all I had, I would recommend something better if you decide to make it but it gets the job done. You also might not even have to do this if you print the hull with thinner tighter layers)

description.text:
This was a small 3d printed model I did for a young student, Kayla Keriazes, who was rowing with her prep school crew. She wanted to explore the effect of various hull coatings in a test tank for a science project and had the hull printed at Skinner Models. The school used the Vespoli 4+ Advantage hull but would not provide her with a design file so I reverse engineered one in Rhino3D from direct dimensions that she took as well as photos and what I could glean from the Vespoli website. I have done many such marine design projects working from photos as well as original design.

https://sketchfab.com/models/1ddc37648ae7410a85f5dbd6e6bd5818

https://www.vespoli.com/boats/fours.php

http://www.skinnermodels.com/portfolio.htm

This was modeled in Rhino3d and the submitted to a professional model making firm as an iges file for FDM printing.

This is how the science project fared from a letter from the student. 

" Sorry it has taken me this long to update you on the project. My partner and I were extremely pleased to find that the Speedo material (that biomimicked sharkskin) actually did make the model boat go faster and decreased its drag coefficient by 25% which means that it reduced the most drag. We put our presentation together and got it printed on a huge board to use to present at fairs. It really came out nice.  
    I attended a science fair at Molloy College this past month and presented my project with my partner. The judges seemed really impressed with our ideas and findings. They really liked the model boats too! We were pleased to find out this past week that my project placed in the top 10% at the fair and I will be given an award at the Awards Breakfast that will take place on April 18th. I won’t know exactly what place/award I will be getting until the breakfast. This is just the first science fair that I was invited to. I will be presenting at others and I will let you know if I receive any other awards.  
    I would just like to thank you once again for all of your help. I cannot explain how much I appreciate it. Without you, this project would have not been possible.

Sincerely,
Kayla Keriazes"

Update to show coins used to ballast the model. Four quarters and one penny brought the model down to about where four oarsmen (oarsgirls?) and one coxswain would on the full size vessel.

description.text:
One weak part on the replicator 2x is the cable to the x-stepper motor.
It will break sooner or later. Put this Stepperpart on the plastic where the stepper motor is.
Then take the 2 cables and put them in the slot of the stepperpart you just fasten.In the edge of your replicator 2x you see the cable is fasten with a clip. you can release the upper clip so the cable get get more room and release some stress on it. The start with the StepperChain.Start with the black cable and move it in the slots on the stepperChains parts.
After you done that you can fasten in on the StepperPart. Now get the StepperFrame and put the cables in that. Fasten the StepperFrame to the StepperChain. Maker sure the cables i in the middle and is not miss align anywhere. Now fasten the StepperFrame to the replicator 2x frame. Make sure you have clearance, so no cable is damage.
I used double sided tape for this. UPDATE
I have made an update on the StepperPart. It is little smaller so it will not hit the screw in the front of the bot. I did add some extra material ontop of it so it should not be any weaker.

I made this with 123d Design.
I also tried makerware at medium setting and all default. Just to make sure it works for all people.
But I then used 0.15mm to print it out. Also the StepperPart and the StepperFrame I made solid. The StepperChain I used 20% infill.
You are free to use what you want, but it would be better if you made all part solid, so they not break. If the part is not friction free then you might want to use a drill and make the hole totally round. They almost newer is when you print. Also the StepperChain link that is fasten to the StepperPart you might need to file/sand down the edge so it move more free or it will break.
